Course 1: Python for Offensive Security

The Hacker's Swiss Army Knife
Module 1: The Hacker's Toolkit (Core Python)

    File I/O, strings/bytes, regular expressions for log analysis

    Subprocess for tool chaining

    Project: Write a fuzzer for a simple server

    Security Link: Data parsing bugs, input validation

Module 2: Binary Manipulation & Protocol Hacking

    struct module, raw socket programming

    Crafting custom packets/headers

    Project: TCP proxy that intercepts/modifies traffic

    Security Link: MITM concepts, protocol reverse engineering

Module 3: Exploit Development & Payload Crafting

    Using pwntools, generating pattern strings

    Calculating offsets, ROP gadget searching

    Project: Automate solving a simple stack buffer overflow

    Security Link: Bridge between vulnerability and exploit

Module 4: Web Exploitation Tooling

    requests, BeautifulSoup, session handling

    Automating CSRF/XSS discovery

    Project: Parameter brute-forcer and SQLi detection script

    Security Link: Web vulnerability classes at protocol level

Module 5: Post-Exploitation & Automation

    Writing keyloggers (conceptual), persistence scripts

    Credential harvesters (for labs)

    Project: Command & Control (C2) prototype

    Security Link: Attacker's operational workflow

Capstone: Multi-module exploit framework
Course 2: C & Assembly: The Exploit Developer's Core

Understanding Memory Corruption
Module 1: Memory Corruption 101

    Pointers, arrays, strcpy/sprintf

    Heap allocators (malloc/free)

    Project: Write intentionally vulnerable programs

    Security Link: Creating lab targets

Module 2: The Stack Frame as Attack Surface

    Dissecting prologue/epilogue

    Return address location, stack canaries

    Project: Manually overwrite return address in debugger

    Security Link: Classic stack buffer overflow

Module 3: Defeating Modern Protections

    DEP/NX: Introduction to ROP

    ASLR: Information leaks, GOT/PLT exploitation

    Stack Canaries: Leaking/defeating them

    Project: Exploit non-executable stack using ROP

    Security Link: Real-world exploit development

Module 4: Heap Exploitation Fundamentals

    Understanding glibc's malloc implementation

    Use-After-Free (UAF), double-free

    Project: Exploit simple UAF to gain code execution

    Security Link: Modern exploit targets

Module 5: Shellcoding & Payload Engineering

    Position-independent, null-free shellcode

    Encoders/decoders

    Project: Reverse TCP shell in ASM for x86_64/ARM

    Security Link: Final payload delivery

Capstone: Full-chain exploit combining info leak + heap UAF
Course 3: JavaScript & Browser Exploitation

The Modern Attack Surface
Module 1: The Browser as Attack Vector

    DOM-based XSS, prototype pollution

    Client-side deserialization

    Project: Find/exploit XSS in vulnerable web app

    Security Link: Beyond alert boxes to credential theft

Module 2: Attacking the JavaScript Engine

    JIT engines, type confusion, array buffer exploitation

    Project: Analyze simplified type confusion PoC

    Security Link: Path to browser RCE

Module 3: Node.js & Server-Side JS Exploitation

    eval() injection, module hijacking

    Deserialization attacks

    Project: Exploit Node.js deserialization bug for RCE

    Security Link: Expanding web attack surface

Module 4: Deobfuscation & Malware Analysis

    Unpacking obfuscated JS

    Control flow analysis, debugging

    Project: Analyze malicious skimmer script

    Security Link: Threat intelligence skill

Capstone: Chain DOM XSS → prototype pollution → Node.js backend compromise
Course 4: SQL & Database Exploitation

*Beyond ' OR 1=1--*
Module 1: Advanced SQL Injection

    Union-based, error-based, blind (time/boolean)

    Out-of-band (DNS/OAST) exfiltration

    Project: Automate blind SQLi to extract schema

    Security Link: Moving beyond basic injection

Module 2: Database-Specific Attacks

    MySQL: INTO OUTFILE for webshells

    PostgreSQL: Large object abuse for RCE

    MSSQL: xp_cmdshell and linked servers

    Project: Use SQLi to achieve full RCE

    Security Link: Escalating from data theft to system compromise

Module 3: Post-Exploitation Database Pivoting

    Stealing password hashes

    Abusing database links for lateral movement

    Project: Escalate from low-privilege SQL to DBA/SA

    Security Link: Database as foothold in enterprise

Module 4: NoSQL Injection & Emerging Tech

    MongoDB injection, GraphQL batching/DoS

    Caching attacks (Redis)

    Project: Exploit NoSQL injection to bypass auth

    Security Link: Modern applications beyond SQL

Capstone: Blind SQLi → file write → steal master key → lateral movement
Course 5: Reverse Engineering for Exploit Development

The Ultimate Synthesis
Module 1: Static Analysis Fundamentals

    IDA/Ghidra basics

    Understanding compiler-generated code

    Project: Manually reverse engineer binary to find buffer overflow

    Security Link: Recognizing vulnerable patterns

Module 2: Dynamic Analysis & Debugging

    Debuggers (x64dbg, GDB with PEDA)

    Breakpoints, tracing, memory watchpoints

    Project: Bypass crackme license check, find hidden vuln

    Security Link: Live analysis skills

Module 3: Windows Internals for Reverse Engineers

    PE format, Windows APIs

    SEH (Structured Exception Handling) exploitation

    Project: Exploit stack overflow with SEH overwrite

    Security Link: Windows-specific techniques

Module 4: Linux Binary Analysis

    ELF format, PLT/GOT hijacking

    dl-resolve exploitation

    Project: Perform ret2dlresolve attack

    Security Link: Linux-specific techniques

Module 5: Real-World Bug Hunting Workflow

    Patch diffing (Microsoft Tuesday patches)

    Fuzzing (AFL++ basics)

    Source code auditing for 1-days

    Project: Analyze patched vulnerability, write exploit for unpatched

    Security Link: Professional bug hunting

Capstone: Full vulnerability discovery to exploit: Fuzz → triage → reverse → weaponize
Course 6: Rootkit Development - The Art of Staying Hidden

Advanced Persistence and Evasion
Module 1: Introduction to Stealth & Persistence

    Philosophy of hiding, persistence mechanisms

    Detection vectors

    Project: Simple userland backdoor with basic hiding

    Security Link: Understanding attacker mindset

Module 2: Userland Rootkits - Hooking & Interception

    LD_PRELOAD hijacking

    PLT/GOT hooking, inline function hooking

    VDSO hooking

    Project: LD_PRELOAD rootkit that hides files/processes

    Security Link: Shared library mechanics

Module 3: Direct Kernel Object Manipulation (DKOM)

    Manipulating kernel data structures from userland

    Linux: /proc/pid manipulation

    Windows: EPROCESS/ETHREAD manipulation

    Project: DKOM rootkit that hides process on Linux

    Security Link: Kernel data structure knowledge

Module 4: Kernel Module Rootkits (Linux)

    Writing legitimate LKMs

    Syscall table hooking, IDT hooking

    Kernel function trampolines

    Project: Kernel module that hooks sys_getdents and sys_kill

    Security Link: Kernel integrity mechanisms

Module 5: Windows Kernel Rootkits

    Windows Driver Foundation basics

    SSDT hooking, filter drivers

    Object Manager callbacks

    Project: Windows driver that hides process and file

    Security Link: Windows driver model

Module 6: Advanced Evasion & Anti-Forensics

    Direct hardware access, hypervisor-based rootkits

    Bootkits, firmware rootkits

    Anti-debugging/anti-VM in kernel space

    Project: Extend kernel module with detection evasion

    Security Link: Hardware security concepts

Module 7: Covert Communications & Data Exfiltration

    Network protocol rootkits

    Covert channels (ICMP, DNS tunneling)

    SSL/TLS interception at kernel level

    Project: Covert channel rootkit with DNS exfiltration

    Security Link: Network stealth techniques

Module 8: Rootkit Detection & Analysis

    Cross-view detection

    Integrity checking, behavioral analysis

    Memory forensics with Volatility

    Project: Rootkit detector comparing ps with /proc

    Security Link: Defensive perspective

Module 9: Modern Hardware-Based Attacks

    UEFI/BIOS rootkits

    AMD PSP/Intel ME vulnerabilities

    GPU-based rootkits, Thunderbolt DMA attacks

    Project: Research/document real hardware vulnerability

    Security Link: Supply chain attacks

Module 10: Legal & Ethical Framework

    Computer Fraud and Abuse Act (CFAA)

    Responsible disclosure, bug bounty programs

    Working with vendors

    Project: Responsible disclosure report for hypothetical vuln

    Security Link: Professional ethics

Capstone: Multi-layered rootkit with bootkit + kernel module + userland + covert comms + evasion
Integration & Progression Strategy
Cross-Course Projects:

    Python scanner → finds open ports → SQL logs results → JavaScript dashboard → triggers C binary → analyze in ASM

    Chain: Web vuln (JS) → Database compromise (SQL) → Privilege escalation (C/ASM) → Persistence (Rootkit)

Skill Progression:
text

Basic Tools (Python) → Memory Understanding (C/ASM) → 
Web/Database (JS/SQL) → Analysis (RE) → Advanced (Rootkits)

Final Meta-Project:

Multi-stage exploit that:

    Discovers vulnerable service via Python scanner

    Exploits SQL injection for initial access

    Uploads malicious JavaScript parsed by internal tool

    Triggers memory corruption in JS engine (C++ component)

    Deploys C/ASM shellcode for persistence

    Student analyzes shellcode via reverse engineering

Lab Environment Requirements
Minimum Setup:
bash

# Virtualization stack
VMware/VirtualBox with nested virtualization
KVM/QEMU for advanced scenarios

# Linux development
Custom kernels with debugging symbols
CONFIG_KPROBES, CONFIG_DEBUG_INFO enabled

# Windows development
Test-signed drivers environment
Windows Driver Kit (WDK)
Separate test machines

# Tools
IDA Pro/Ghidra (free version OK for learning)
GDB with PEDA/Pwndbg extensions
WinDbg/KD for Windows
Volatility for memory forensics
AFL++ for fuzzing

Safety Protocols:

    Air-gapped lab networks only

    No internet connectivity for infected machines

    Regular snapshots for recovery

    Documentation of all experiments

    Clear boundaries between lab and production

Real-World Applications for White Hats
Career Paths:

    Red Team Operator: Testing enterprise detection

    Malware Analyst: Understanding APTs

    Kernel Security Researcher: Finding OS vulnerabilities

    Forensic Tool Developer: Creating detection tools

    IoT Security Researcher: Embedded systems security

Bug Bounty Specializations:

    Memory corruption in web apps (WASM, browser engines)

    Kernel/driver vulnerabilities

    Protocol implementation flaws

    Hardware/firmware vulnerabilities

Suggested Reading & Resources
Books:

    "The Shellcoder's Handbook" - Chris Anley et al.

    "Rootkits: Subverting the Windows Kernel" - Greg Hoglund & Jamie Butler

    "The Art of Software Security Assessment" - Dowd, McDonald, Schuh

    "Practical Malware Analysis" - Michael Sikorski & Andrew Honig

    "A Bug Hunter's Diary" - Tobias Klein

Online Resources:

    Phrack Magazine (historical but relevant)

    MITRE ATT&CK Framework

    OWASP Web Security Testing Guide

    Kernel.org documentation

    Intel/AMD architecture manuals

Academic Papers:

